d stop.’ They propose the food industry could sell unhealthy foods in red packaging to help curb overeating or that bars could serve alcohol in red cups so that people won’t have as much to drink. To come up with their results, 41 male students drank tea from cups marked with either red or blue labels. The students drank 44 percent less from the red cups. To test eating habits, 109 people were served ten pretzels each, either on red, blue, or white plates. Those with red plates ate less pretzels than the rest. Click here to read more on this story from The Daily Mail. Share This Article Newsletter Signup Sign up for free e-mail news alerts from FoxNews.com and FoxBusiness.com. Newsletter Signup View Article Please enable JavaScript to view the comments powered by Disqus. You must login to comment. View Article Advertisement Top Health Centers Back Pain Beauty & Skin Cancer Cholesterol Cold and Flu Depression Digestive Health Heart Disease Nutrition Pain Management Pregnancy Sexual Health View All Health Centers » FOLLOW FOX NEWS HEALTH Young Guns Betting on Financial News Startup Benzinga Marketing Startup That Doesn't Feel Manufactured Young Guns Reloaded: Wedding Bells, Babies and Business Young Guns: Organic Baby Food Soars More › Latest Health Videos Trending In Health 1 Prevent cancer with ‘poor man’s pepper’ 2 Louisiana toddler dies after 2-year battle with rare skin disease 3 Transplant nurse donates kidney to patient 4 Serious injuries triple for headphone-wearing pedestrians 5 Woman loses arm, shoulder after injecting bath salts See all trends Advertisement Meaning Of Fingers Healthy Eating And Education Running Playlist Don't Bring Her To The Gym College Football Programs 7 steps to instant calm How to fight stubborn heartburn Fibromyalgia: a tricky diagnosis 12 secrets for better orgasms Diet tips for Crohn's disease German ZEW Econ. Sentiment Gauge Rises In January Euro-zone December Annual Inflation Falls To 2.7% U.K. CPI Inflation Drops To 4.2% In Dece